A physicist, a biologist, and a chemist were going to the ocean for the first time. The physicist saw the ocean and was fascinated by the waves. He said he wanted to do some research on the fluid dynamics of the waves and walked into the ocean. Unfortunately, he drowned and never returned. The biologist said he wanted to research the flora and fauna inside the ocean and walked in. He too, unfortunately, drowned and never returned. The chemist waited for a long time, then wrote the observation in his journal: "The physicist and the biologist are soluble in ocean water." He then concluded, "Humans are not a sustainable species when exposed to oceanic conditions for extended periods of time without proper survival equipment."

A farmer, an engineer, and a mathematician are each tasked with building the most efficient fence to enclose a flock of sheep. The farmer constructs a square fence, claiming it's the most practical shape. The engineer opts for a circular fence, arguing it provides the maximum area with the least amount of material. The mathematician, however, builds a fence that follows the exact contour of the flock, stating, \"I define the boundary to be the outermost sheep!\" Confused, the farmer and engineer ask for an explanation. The mathematician responds, \"In mathematics, it's all about setting the right boundaries. By positioning the fence along the outermost sheep, I've effectively enclosed the flock with the least amount of material, making it the most efficient solution of all!\" The farmer and engineer nod, intrigued by the mathematician's unconventional approach, while the sheep continue to graze, blissfully unaware of the complex reasoning behind their enclosure.
